    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>Why are stocks falling today?</summary>
        <p>Stocks generally fall due to a combination of negative macroeconomic data (like rising inflation or unexpected job losses), actions by the Federal Reserve (like raising interest rates), geopolitical tensions, or poor corporate earnings reports from major companies that drag down the entire index.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What should I do when stocks are falling?</summary>
        <p>For long-term investors, the best thing to do is usually nothing. Avoid panic selling. If you have extra cash, a market drop can be a great buying opportunity to purchase high-quality stocks or index funds at a discount.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does interest rates affect the stock market?</summary>
        <p>When the Federal Reserve raises interest rates, borrowing money becomes more expensive for companies and consumers. This slows down economic growth and reduces corporate profits, making stocks less attractive, which usually causes prices to fall.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Will the stock market ever recover?</summary>
        <p>Historically, the U.S. stock market has always recovered from every single crash, recession, and depression in history, eventually going on to reach new all-time highs. However, recovery can take months or even years.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a market correction?</summary>
        <p>A market correction is defined as a drop of 10% or more from a recent high. It is a normal, healthy part of the market cycle that helps reset valuations. A drop of 20% or more is considered a 'bear market'.</p>
      </details>

    </section>
